<p> <h3><center> Barnsley <a NAME="chop">chop</a> may disappear from menu</center></h3>


                                             
BY MICHAEL HORNSBY, AGRICULTURE CORRESPONDENT, AND DIANA THORP <br>
 July 24 1996 .. The Times<p>
<i>Scare over sheep spines may mean ban on historic British speciality </i>:<p>

                THE Barnsley chop, one of Britain's most celebrated national dishes, may disappear from
                menus if the European Union's proposed ban on sheep offal goes ahead. 

                The inclusion of the spinal cord in the ban would affect traditional cuts which include the
                backbone, such as saddle of lamb, the Barnsley chop and rosettes, in all of which the spinal
                cord is left in place. <p>

                But Douglas Hogg, the Agriculture Minister, said in Brussels yesterday that any ban on the
                spinal cord was likely to apply only to sheep over 12 months old. 

                Most British lambs are slaughtered at less than a year. None of the proposed restrictions
                would apply to lambs under six months old. <p>

                The Asda supermarket chain welcomed the proposed measures. "All our lamb is new-season
                and under six months old, so I understand it would not come under these regulations," a
                spokesman said. Asda and Marks & Spencer said that spinal cord was already removed from
                their lamb. 

                Diane McCrea, of the Consumers' Association, urged consumers to await the announcement
                of new government guidelines. "Lots of people have been turning to lamb from beef, but
                they should not panic and should wait to see what the recommendations are." <p>

                The proposed restrictions on the sale of sheep's brain and spleen should have little effect on
                sales in Britain, as there is little or no market for such items. Spleen is not eaten and
                brain has a tiny market, mostly among some Muslim communities, although the Ministry of
                Agriculture, Food and Fisheries urged people in the Outer Hebrides to stop making their
                traditional dish of sheep's head soup. <p>

                The broth, which involves boiling the sheep's head, has been prepared as a delicacy for
                centuries in the Western Isles and the recipe occurs in many local cookbooks. However,
                there have been no recorded cases of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease in the Outer Hebrides in the
                wake of the current BSE scare. <p>

                A spokesman from the Meat and Livestock Association said that 95 per cent of sheep's heads
                were destroyed in Britain because they had little economic value. All other cuts of lamb,
                including mince, haggis, shoulder, leg, breast and rack, would not be affected by such a ban.

                He said that few consumers today cooked the neck rings, usually used for stewing, or the
                saddle of lamb, which is rarely sold in shops and is used mainly by caterers for roasting. <p>

                The main casualty of a ban would be the double loin chop, or Barnsley chop. Richard North,
                of the Quality Meats Association, said that a ban on spinal cord would put an end to the
                Yorkshire speciality which is actually two chops joined by a piece of backbone. "It's the
                customers' favourite chop, and it's certainly my favourite," Dr North said. "But if the ban
                comes into operation, that'll be it; it'll go out the window." <p>

                Nick Pound, chef and joint owner of the Barnsley restaurant Armstrongs, said the loss of
                the Barnsley chop would mean the end of one of the country's few regional dishes and would
                be akin to the loss of the Cumberland sausage or Banbury cake. "It was named after the
                Prince Regent ate it at the King's Hotel in Barnsley and it has been popular ever since." 

                But he added that the dangers of contracting disease from spinal cord would be minimal, as a
                consumer would have to break down the spine of the chop to get to the spinal cord. <p>

                Moyra Fraser, cooking editor of Good Housekeeping, did not think a ban would cause panic.
                "Not many people in Britain eat lamb brains and, as long as chops have been well butchered
                and had the spinal column fully removed, there should be no cause for concern." <p>
<h3><center><a NAME="Historic">Historic</a> Cattle Market Succumbs</center></h3>

        A 136-year-old cattle market closed yesterday, the latest victim of the BSE crisis.
                Barry Hawkins, a livestock auctioneer, sold his last cattle from the market in King's Lynn,
                Norfolk, which had been established by his great-grandfather in 1860. 

                Mr Hawkins, 50, has seen the number of cows passing through his market fall from 80 to
                20 a day. "BSE has closed us down," he said. "It was a cock-up by the Government. <p>


                "The number of cattle we were selling dropped and so have the prices, by 30 per cent.
                There was no way we could continue. It has been a very hard decision." 

                Livestock breeders will now have to take their cattle to market in Norwich and Bury St
                Edmunds. <hr>

               <h3><center>New Zealand, <a NAME="Australia">Australia</a> scramble to squelch rumors</center></h3>
Australian officials said that the country had diligent systems in place to prevent scrapie,
                and <strong>allegations that Australian sheep were infected were ludicrous</strong>. 
______________

The New Zealand Government said yesterday that it was seeking more detail on European
                scientific evidence that BSE could be passed to sheep through feed derived from infected
                cattle remains, but officials doubted whether the link was new. 

                An Agriculture Ministry spokesman said: "We're not familiar with that research or the
                methodology used. It's always been known that scrapie and BSE are similar."<p>
 

               New Zealand has about 50 million sheep and exports more than 90 per cent of the lamb it
                processes each year, with Britain providing the largest market. It has an annual quota of
                225,000 tonnes for lamb, mutton and goat exports to the EU. <p>

                Stuart McDermott, manager of agricultural security at the ministry, said: "Excuse me if
                I'm underwhelmed, but the prevailing view is that BSE is scrapie that came from sheep into
                cattle through the practice of feeding cattle on meat and bone meal. I really don't see what is
                new." 

                He added that New Zealand had a <b>voluntary ban</b> on the feeding of meat and bone meal to
                ruminants.           
<hr>
         
<h3><center>Dictionary of Lamb <a NAME="Products">Products</a></center></h3>

               <li> <strong>Main cuts of lamb:</strong> neck, shoulder, loin, chump, chump chops, leg, breast, baron,
                saddle. 

              <li>  <strong>Poorer cuts:</strong> mince. 

                <li><strong>Mechanically recovered meat (MRM):</strong> edible tissues not stripped from bones to same
                extent as cows, but vegetarian groups claim low-quality lamb MRM is found in pies. Also in
                beef and pork sausages, burgers and pet food. 
<li><strong>Sweetbreads: </strong>Thymus gland, used in <i>ris de veau    </i>  or 

          <ul>      <li><strong>Brains:</strong> lamb's brains are French delicacy, <i>cervelle d'agneau</i>, <i>t&ecirc;te de veau </i> is calf's head
<li><strong>Haggis:</strong> Pudding made of lungs, heart, liver, minced with suet, boiled in sheep stomach
                <li><strong>Bones:</strong> fertiliser. Use in feeds stopped in April. 

                <li><strong>Keratin:</strong> protein in horns and hooves used in shampoos. 

                <li><strong>Elastin: </strong>protein uniting muscle fibres used in moisturisers. 

                <li><strong>Lanolin:</strong> fat extracted from sheep's wool. 

                <li><strong>Cholecalciferol (D3):</strong> vitamin derived from lanolin. 

                <li><strong>Gelatin:</strong> mostly from cows, some may come from sheep.</ul>
<hr>

<hr> 
<center><h3>Market <a NAME="prices">prices</a> fall by 20% in one day </h3></center>


                       July 24 1996       ... London Times ...                                          BY MICHAEL HORNSBY <p>

                 BRITAIN'S 90,000 sheep farmers were bracing themselves yesterday for a slump in
                 consumer demand after the disclosure that some sheep products are to be banned because of
                 fears that they may be infected with "mad cow" disease. 

                 Up to now the sheep industry, which earns farmers some £1.2 billion a year in domestic
                 sales and a further £280 million in exports, has been one of the beneficiaries of the beef
                 crisis as consumers have switched to other meats. <p>

                 The first signs of panic were reflected yesterday in falls of up to 20 per cent in sheep
                 prices at livestock markets, which knocked up to £8 off the price of a lamb. 

                 Prices fell to about 95p a kg compared with about 115p this time last week, wiping out
                 much of the gains lamb prices have made since the BSE crisis broke in March. Farmers
                 were hoping yesterday that consumers would not panic and would see the ban as a purely
                 precautionary measure against a theoretical risk. <p>

                 Ieuan Lewis, who keeps 500 breeding ewes near Llangollen, North Wales, said: "I hope
                 people are not going to overreact. Even if there is only a theoretical risk of spongiform
                 encephalopathy getting into sheep, I hope they will accept that it is better to be upfront and
                 take the necessary precautions." 

                 He added: "Recently our lamb prices have greatly improved on the back of the fall in the
                 beef trade. Last week I sold 51 lambs for 117p a kilogram. This time last year I was getting
                 less than 100p." <p>

                 The higher income from his sheep has helped to offset the loss Mr Lewis has been suffering
                 on his beef cattle. Cattle prices are about £100 an animal lower than a year ago and Mr
                 Lewis is running up big feed bills as he keeps cattle back on his farm in hope of market
                 improvement. 

                 Colin Maclean, director-general of the Meat and Livestock Commission, said: "About 95 per
                 cent of sheep carcasses already have their head removed at the abattoir and the spleen is not
                 used. So these measures should have virtually no impact on our industry. <p>

                 "Although there is no evidence of spongiform encephalopathy in sheep, and although scrapie
                 has been around in sheep for 250 years and never been found to present any hazard to
                 humans, it is always better to err on the side of caution." 

                 But Anthony Gibson, the National Farmers' Union's regional director for southwest England,
                 criticised Franz Fischler, the European Agriculture Commissioner, for proposing the ban.
                 "It is completely unjustified," he said. "Scrapie has been studied for centuries and there is
                 absolutely no evidence of any link to BSE." <p>

                 Marks & Spencer said there had been no change in the price of lamb since the BSE scare.
                 However, it has introduced a lamb special this week which has reduced the prices. 

                 Safeway said demand increased significantly after the BSE scare, but had now decreased and
                 stabilised at a level still higher than before BSE. <p>

                 Organic lamb has decreased in price since the BSE scare. Tim Finney, an organic meat
                 wholesaler from Swindon Butcher, said the price of lamb had gone down from £3.30 per kg
                 to £2.70. "If the lamb price collapses we will ignore it. It might even increase our price
                 because people appreciate we farm in a completely different way." <p>


<hr>

<h3><center> <a NAME="Infected">Infected</a> feed may lead to new strain of scrapie</center></h3>
    July 24 1996 .. London Times .... Michael Hornsby<p>

                 THE move to ban certain lamb and goat products follows research showing that "mad cow"
                 disease could be transmitted artificially to sheep in laboratory tests). 

                 Scientists disagree about the significance of the finding, but accept that it may be better to
                 err on the side of caution in removing even the most theoretical health threat from eating
                 lamb. <p>

                 Scrapie Ç spongiform encephalopathy in sheep Ç has not hitherto caused humans any
                 apparent harm. The brain condition Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease affects one in a million
                 people, even in countries with no scrapie. 

                 What is worring scientists is that sheep might have acquired a new strain of scrapie from
                 eating meat and bone meal derived from cattle remains infected with BSE, reversing the
                 process by which cattle are thought to have contracted the disease. <p>

                 John Bourne, director of the Institute of Animal Health at Compton, Berkshire, said: "If
                 BSE has got into sheep, we cannot be absolutely 100 per cent sure that it will behave
                 identically to scrapie and pose no risk to humans." <p>

                 Research by the institute in 1993 found that BSE could be transmitted to sheep by feeding
                 them infected brain tissue from cattle or by injecting it into their brains. Infectivity was
                 detected in the brains and spleen. More recent work by the institute, published last month
                 in The Veterinary Record, discovered that spleen tissue from these artificially infected
                 sheep produce a pattern of disease when injected into laboratory mice that is similar to that
                 caused by BSE material from cattle. <p>

                 "It has to be emphasised that we have been unable so far to detect any sign of a new strain of
                 scrapie that might indicate that BSE has got into sheep in the field," Professor Bourne said.
                 "But it may be that we have not been looking hard enough." <p>

                 Scientists have transmitted BSE orally to goats and mice as well as to sheep. Pigs have been
                 infected, but only by injection into the brain. Chickens are resistant to infection either
                 orally or by inoculation. The Government's spongiform encephalopathy advisory committee
                 (SEAC) is recommending that sheep brain and spleen be excluded from the human food
                 chain. <p>

                 In practice, no lamb spleen is eaten and 95 per cent of carcasses have their heads removed
                 at the abattoir. In Britain, only some Muslims are thought to eat sheep's brains. Scientists
                 see no danger in muscle meat, or in liver and kidney. <p>

                 Some European scientists want spinal cord covered by the ban as well, at any rate in sheep
                 older than 12 months, though their British colleagues are not entirely convinced. Such a
                 ban could affect some traditional cuts in which the backbone remains attached. <p>

                 Britain has banned feeding meat and bone meal to sheep since July 1988. Although farmers
                 used to give breeding ewes meat and bone meal as a protein supplement, most lambs are fed
                 almost entirely on grass. Exposure to infected feed would thus have been much less than in
                 cattle. <p>


                 Francis Anthony, past president of the British Veterinary Association, said: "This seems to
                 be carrying the precautionary principle to ridiculous lengths. Sheep deliberately infected
                 with BSE do not itch and rub themselves against fence posts, as classical cases of scrapie. If
                 sheep were suffering from a new kind of scrapie, we would have noticed." 


<hr>
<center><h3>Europe tries to <a NAME="avert">avert</a> panic on 'mad sheep'</h3></center>

BY CHARLES BREMNER AND MICHAEL HORNSBY<br>
The Times: Britain:July 24 1996<p>

EUROPEAN officials were trying to smother a "mad sheep" crisis yesterday as livestock markets showed the first signs of panic and prices fell by up to 20 per cent.


With ministers insisting that sheep were most unlikely to contract BSE, the Farm Commissioner Franz Fischler came under attack for kindling the latest flare-up in the "mad cow" saga.

<p>

Loyola de Palacio, the Spanish Farm Minister, said that Herr Fischler's statement calling for a ban on some sheep and goat offal had achieved the opposite of his intention of reassuring consumers. "This has provoked unjustified and extremely serious fears," she said. And Ivan Yates, the Irish minister, appealed for a sense of proportion. "It is important to learn the lessons of the last six months with BSE. It is quite easy to strike a match and cause a forest fire with regard to BSE. It is more difficult to put it out."

<p>

The Commission decided to call for a ban on the use of brain, spinal cord and spleen from goats and sheep after scientists in France and Scotland found that some sheep contracted BSE after being fed infected brain tissue from cattle. The French researchers found that half a gramme of infected tissue was enough to transmit the disease in some cases. But there is no evidence that sheep on farms had ever been infected.

<p>

Brussels is acting partly under pressure from the French Government, whose advisers suspect that BSE is being under-reported and could be affecting a range of animals, including cats and mink. France has already banned consumption of brain tissue and has imposed strict rules on the production of animal-based feed.


Now the Commission wants to extend some of the restrictions across the EU, not so much to protect humans as to remove the risk of other animals contracting BSE.


Douglas Hogg, the Agriculture Minister, is expected to tell MPs today that Britain is willing to go along with that and yesterday he said there was no need for a lamb crisis "if people are sensible". The measures proposed would exclude from the food chain parts of the animal that were not eaten anyway. "I believe that lamb throughout Europe is wholly safe," he said.

<p>

The only cuts likely to be affected by a ban would be saddle of lamb, which includes the backbone, the Barnsley chop, which has a section of spine at its centre, and rosette of lamb from the neck. But even these could continue to be produced as usual, since removal of the spinal cord was likely to be required only if the animal was more than a year old &#173; and most lambs are slaughtered before that age.

Some meat industry and farmers' leaders agreed that the proposed ban was prudent, but even so, lamb prices at British markets fell from &#163;1.15 per kg last week to 95p.
<hr>


<h3><center>New <a NAME="link">link</a> between mad cow disease and sheep</center></h3>

Nando.net aand Associated Press July 24, 1996<p>
LONDON  -- Findings that mad cow disease may be transmitted from cows to other animals are expected to prompt Britain to ban parts of sheep and goat offal from the human food chain.<p>


   Agriculture Minister Douglas Hogg will announce the ban on the use of sheep and goat brains, spinal cords and spleens in the human food chain later this week, Independent Television News reported.

   Experiments at the Institute of Animal Health in Edinburgh showed that sheep and goats could catch bovine spongiform encephalopathy, known as mad cow disease.<p>

   European Union Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler announced plans Monday to introduce a similar ban Europe-wide amid fears of a link between sheep and BSE.

   EU farm ministers meeting in Brussels said the plan was only precautionary, designed to shore up consumer confidence in meat.

   Europe's meat crisis was sparked on March 20 when the British government reported an apparent link between mad cow disease, a fatal illness that destroys the brains of cattle, and its human equivalent, Creutzfeld Jakob Disease.

   About 10 people in Britain have died of the disease. One man died of it in France this year.<p>

   Scrapie, a disease similar to BSE, has been common in sheep for hundreds of years without harm to human health. The experiments carried out in Scotland showed that sheep who were fed or infected with BSE material caught BSE rather than than the more harmless scrapie. British meat industry spokesmen demanded more research before action was taken.<hr>



  
<h3><center>Scrapie <a NAME="Eradication">Eradication</a> Attempts</center></h3>

Listserve Item 24 July 1996<p>

What experiments of Foster et al do show is that experimentally, by
inoculation or orally, it is possible to infect sheep with BSE and it
appears as BSE, The strain-typing results show clearly that the
encephalopathy is BSE and _not_ scrapie and that the two are _not_ the
same.<p>

 
Turning to Robert's enquiry, compared with the very considerable
amount of public  and media comment on BSE in recent years, there has
been little public comment in the media -- or therefore among the
public -- about scrapie [either before 1987 or since] because scrapie
has never been perceived by the UK media, or the public or the
authorities or scientists as being a food safety issue.<p>
 
 It was, and is, an important issue of agricultural management and
economics, and over the years a great deal of research has been done
on scrapie, particularly in the UK Institute for Animal Health
[summaries of recent research may be accessed on their Web site at
<http://www.iah.bbsrc.ac.uk/institut/public/reports/1995/3wtse.htm>]<p>
 
Scrapie being endemic in the UK, its eradication is extremely
difficult, the more so because scrapie is subject to vertical and
horizontal transmission.  I understand that it was the latter
characteristics that defeated an attempted regulatory program in USA
in the 1950s (ref. Dr Randall Cutlip, Respiratory and Neurological
Disease Research Unit, Agricultural Research Service, USDA, answering
a question on scrapie at the IFT Special Forum on BSE, New Orleans, 23
June 1996).<p>
 
The approach to eradication is along the lines of trying to identify
genetic variation(s)  among sheep that are scrapie-resistant, and
selective use of rams that carry that trait, plus prudent importation
and husbandry.. If it can be done it will be a lengthy process,
probably a decade or more.<p>
 
An additional complication is that there appear to be different
strains of scrapie, influenced not only by the PrP sequence but by
other as yet unknown factors.<p>
 
Although the US experiments, at Ames, Iowa and Mission, Texas
inoculating cattle with scrapie and producing neurological disease
which, however, did not resemble BSE, may appear to undermine the
hypothesis that scrapie was the agent in the incriminated meal and
bonemeal that originally started the UK BSE epidemic, it may well be
that the original scrapie culprit was a particular scrapie strain not
used in the US experiments. I doubt if we shall ever know the truth or
otherwise of that hypothesis for certain, or at least until science
has learned more about scrapie strains and the factors involved.
 <hr>


 <h3><center>Lamb <a NAME="Eradication">chops</a> threatened by BSE ban</center></h3>

Lamb chops threatened by BSE ban
 
By Roger Highfield and Toby Helm<br> 
The Telegraph ...Tuesday July 23 1996<p>


THE BSE scare threatened to spread from beef to lamb products last night
after European officials disclosed that they were investigating reports
that the disease could be transmitted to sheep. <p>

Measures extending the ban on possibly infected meat and offal to sheep,
goats and deer are being drawn up by the European Union's agriculture
commissioner, Franz Fischler.Ministers, officials and experts were
trying to avert another food scare by insisting that the latest moves
were purely precautionary. But British veterinary experts said the new
measures would directly affect the way lamb chops were prepared by
butchers. <p>

There was growing concern in Whitehall that new measures could lead to a
slump in sales of lamb. Many consumers switched to other meat, such as
lamb, after the reports earlier this year of a possible link between a
new strain of CJD, the human version of BSE, and products such as
beefburgers. <p>

The British Veterinary Association said the proposed ban on sheep offal
and central nervous tissue was a <b>"ludicrous measure"</b> with no scientific
justification. It would entail removing the spinal cord attached to lamb
chops. The association was strongly supported by Prof Richard Lacey, an
expert on BSE, who strongly criticised Mr Fischler's comments and called
for his resignation. <p>

Prof Lacey, a microbiologist at Leeds University, was one of the first
scientists to give warning of the developing BSE crisis. Although he has
been critical of Government action to eradicate the disease in cattle,
<b>Lacey said Mr Fischler's claims were "completely wrong".</b> <p>

The new concern about sheep stems from research in France into the
disease scrapie - similar to BSE - which has been around for 200 years.
Prof Lacey maintained that BSE in cattle was a new disease, nothing to
do with scrapie.<b> Lacey said Mr Fischler seemed to be completely confused. </b>

'Can we be sure that a case of so-called scrapie is not in fact BSE in
sheep?' <p>

Earlier, Mr Fischler said he was seeking a ban on offal from sheep and
goats, as well as beef, in consumer products and animal feed following
"experimental evidence" that BSE could be transmitted to sheep. This
would include the spleens of sheep and goats as well as tissue from the
central nervous system. Douglas Hogg, the Agriculture Minister, will
make a Commons statement tomorrow setting out the opinion of the
Government's expert advisers. Mr Fischler said he would put the ban to
the Standing Veterinary Committee of the EU within the next 10 days. <p>

Earlier, a report in the French daily Le Monde said that scientists had
warned the European Commission for the first time about the consumption
of offal from sheep and goats. The scientists were concerned with the
ease with which BSE could pass through the food chain from one species
to another. Significantly, experimentally infected sheep showed the
agent maintained all the hallmarks of BSE, and the disease also affected
the spleen as well as the spinal cord and brain. <p>

Mr Fischler said that the experimental evidence raised several
questions. "In particular can we be sure that a case of so-called
scrapie is not in fact BSE in sheep?" Bearing in mind the need to
protect humans from exposure to the BSE agent it was necessary to "err
on the side of caution". "We also need to act positively to restore
public confidence in beef and perhaps to avoid loss of confidence in
other meat," he said. <p>

But his comments risk severe damage to the market for lamb and sheep
products following the slump in consumption of beef across Europe. A
Ministry of Agriculture spokesman said the proposed ban was "a very
precautionary measure". "We are not particularly worried about this. We
in Britain remove 99 per cent of sheep's heads anyway and we don't eat
sheep's brains in this country." <p>

Francis Anthony, BSE adviser to the British Veterinary Association,
said: "We've been living with scrapie for more than 200 years and no
scientist has been able to make a connection between scrapie and man. It
may be possible to transmit BSE to sheep experimentally but there is no
evidence in the field that BSE causes damage to sheep. Otherwise we vets
would be seeing it."
<hr>

<h3><center>Feed Ban <a NAME="Commentary">Commentary</a></center></h3>

Feed Ban Commentary
24 July 96<br>

British Correspondent<p>

<pre>Two articles from todays papers follow. Government and agriculture
sources are wading in reassuring consumers with two premises:

1)     That the problem is scrapie not bse

2)     That the new measures are purely precautionary
</pre>
However, the reality is probably rather different, another newspaper
article (sorry I cant get it online) states that British farmers
continued to use prohibited feed containing mammalian input for SEVEN
years after the stuff was banned for all ruminants. If true it must me
more likely than not that sheep now harbour BSE, and the UK is a major
exporter of sheep all over Europe. Apparently the Agriculture Minister
Hogg (on his own admission in a radio interview) has known of the
problem since April but has taken no action. <p>

All this confirms the widely held view that until the BSE<>CJD link was
made in March this year that government anti-BSE measures were for
cosmetic purposes and were not implemented. Another example is that
offals prohibited in 1988 were still entering animal and human food
chains until this year as the abbatoir regulations were simply not
enforced. It seems that the government thought that it was just scrapie,
that scrapie is known not to be a significant human problem, and that
therefore no substantive action was required.<p>

Mammalian based fertiliser is still manufactured and legal for certain
uses in the UK and mammalian based feed is still manufactured for fish
feed (despite being banned in France), nothing changes.
<hr>


