<TITLE>Inquiry into BSE Cover-up Begins</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<A HREF="#ordered">Ministers ordered before Committee of Inquiry</A>
<P>

<blockquote>
<h3><center>National Ministers <a NAME="ordered">ordered</a> before Committee of Inquiry</center></h3>
Socialist Spokesman, European Parliament<br>
23 July 1996<p>

     Government ministers could be called before a European Parliament
committee of inquiry into mad cow disease, it was revealed in Brussels
today.

     It would be the first time an EU public inquiry summoned national
ministers to give evidence.<p>

     The European Parliament has set up a 19-member inquiry committee
to 'investigate alleged contraventions or maladministration in the
implementation of Community law in relation to BSE.'  

     The inquiry committee's first meeting is to be held on 3 September
in Brussels.  Spanish Socialist leader in the European Parliament Manuel
Medina is to prepare the inquiry report for the end of the year.<p>

     Said Mr Medina in Brussels today:  'In my opinion we should be
calling government ministers.  Most decisions have been made at
government level.  Under the principle of subsidiarity, governments have
the main responsibility for the health of the people.  The committee of
inquiry should therefore seek information from national governments.'<p>

     Mr Medina, an expert in international law, added:  'There is
nothing to prevent the committee of inquiry from calling a member of a
government.  It would be in the interests of governments concerned to
cooperate with the inquiry in order to demonstrate a commitment to
openness and transparency.<p>

     'If public health can be guaranteed, it is through transparency
that we expect public trust in the consumption of beef to be restored.'<p>
<pre>
     A five-page document setting out the committee's brief places
special emphasis on public health questions. 

     Three areas highlighted in the brief are:

     + TRANSPARENCY of the fight against mad cow disease through wide
              publication of research;
     + MONITORING of the beef export ban; and
     + ADOPTION of measures for protection of public health and
              restoration of smooth operation of the markets.</pre><hr></blockquote>



