<HR>

<I>Additional Background and Commentary  provided by Webmaster:</I><P>
<BLOCKQUOTE> Authorities from UDSA-APHIS have been hunting down some of the several hundred cattle imported from Britain that escaped the 1989 ban on live imports.Politically, this is very significant to the meat and dairy industry. However, these animals are utterly insignificant scientifically in view of endemic <STRONG>sheep scrapie</STRONG> and <STRONG>300,000 'downer cows'</STRONG> annually entering the US food chain and <STRONG>continuing use</STRONG> of imported British protein and dietary supplements from infected animals.  Cattle in US definitely have BSE  [however we call it DCS -- downer cattle syndrome].  This disease has been transmitted to mink farms, as per numerous peer-reviewed publications of U. Wisconsin veterinary scientist R.F. Marsh, and quite possibly to two recent youngish human victims in Oregon.<P>
<P>
BSE is a disease that naturally occurs in cattle at low frequency just as scrapie occurs naturally in sheep as mutant alleles of a normal PrP gene, so of course it is present in the U.S.  The question is whether these basal levels have been exacerbated by feeding rendered infected sheep and cattle from either U.S. or British sources.
</BLOCKQUOTE>



