<body bgcolor=ffffff>

<h3> INSTITUTE FOR ANIMAL HEALTH</h3><p>







<H4>TRANSMISSIBLE SPONGIFORM ENCEPHALOPATHIES</H4>



Each research report describes work carried out during 1995 and is directed to research workers

in the area.  No introductory or contextual material is currently available.<p>



<A HREF="#1">Identification of candidate molecular species</A><br>

<A HREF="#2">Changes in RNA</A><br>

<A HREF="#3">Strains of agent</A><br>

<A HREF="#4">Post-transcriptional control of PrP mRNA expression</A><br>

<A HREF="#5">5' and 3' non-coding regions of PrP mRNA</A><br>

<A HREF="#6">PrP structure</A><br>

<A HREF="#7">Cytotoxicity of PrP</A><br>

<A HREF="#8">Recombinant PrP</A><br>

<A HREF="#9">Crystalline PrP</A><br>

<A HREF="#10">Replication of PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP></A><br>

<A HREF="#11">A basis for prophylaxis</A><br>

<A HREF="#12">Markers for susceptibility in sheep</A><br>

<A HREF="#13">An ante-mortem test</A><br>

<A HREF="#14">Natural modes of transmission</A><br>

<A HREF="#15">Transmission of BSE to sheep and goats</A><br>

<A HREF="#16">Rendering methods</A><br>

<A HREF="#17">Rendering under commercial conditions</A><br>

<A HREF="#18">Chemical and physical inactivation</A><br>

<A HREF="#19">Review of autoclave protocols</A><br>

<A HREF="#20">Publications 1995</A>

<p>



<A NAME="1"><h2>Identification of candidate molecular species</h2></A>



The existence of many strains of scrapie, some of which change properties on serial passage,

suggests that the scrapie agent may contain an informational molecule in addition the important

PrP protein.  The simplest hypothesis for its nature is to propose the existence of

a nucleic acid which encodes strain-specific information.  To test this hypothesis a strategy

is being developed whereby any scrapie- specific nucleic acid should be detected, regardless

of its properties.<p>



The basis of the adopted approach is that:<p>



<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>scrapie infectivity can be highly purified with minimal losses - but it is
assumed that any method for purifying nucleic acid from a scrapie infectivity
fraction destroys infectivity, preventing further assay;<p>

<LI>in 1g scrapie-infected brain with a titre of 10<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>10</FONT></SUP> infectious units/g, a minimum
of &gt;1ng nucleic acid M<SUB><i><FONT SIZE=-1>r</FONT></i></SUB> &gt;60,000 is present;<p>

<LI>silver staining can detect 0.1ng of any nucleic acid in scrapie brain extracts,
if it is sufficiently purified, regardless of its structure or properties.<p>
</UL>

Scrapie infectivity is extracted from infected brain using a protocol in which subcellular

fractionation is used to isolate a membrane-rich fraction.  Dissolution in Sarkosyl followed

by centrifugation to sediment particles &gt;50S is performed twice.  Fractions with little loss of

infectivity compared with the initial titre can be recovered.  The extraction protocol has

been modified specifically to remove ferritin, ribosomes and some PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP>, some of the

contaminants which may interfere in the subsequent observation of candidate nucleic acids.<p>



Guanidine extraction and sedimentation through CsCl allowed the recovery of RNA some of

which was sequenced.  Analysis of more highly purified infectivity fractions showed little

difference between control and scrapie fractions.  However, further purification of the scrapie

infectivity fraction removed much of the RNA, allowing a reassessment of whether

differences between control and scrapie samples could be detected.<p>



<A NAME="2"><h2>Changes in RNA</h2></A>



Elevated levels of 7S RNA in scrapie mouse brain have previously been reported.  This work

has been repeated and results obtained using silver staining and slab gels with a scrapie

mouse model have concurred with the earlier observations.  For a BSE mouse model the

results were less clear-cut.  Silver stain is not specific for nucleic acids, and contaminants

could not be distinguished.  Fluorescent dyes specific for DNA and RNA are now being

exploited to resolve this problem. <p>



Several explanations for 7S RNA changes are possible.  A similar elevation has been

reported in Crohn's disease.  Thus this is probably not a scrapie-specific phenomenon and

elevated levels of 7S RNA may be correlated to pathological progression.  Comparison of

the nucleic acids isolated from brains, spleens and blood of scrapie-infected mice during the

incubation period using a 7S-specific probe should resolve the problem.<p>



<A NAME="3"><h2>Strains of agent</h2></A>



The series of strain typing transmissions to mice from nine UK BSE cattle sources, collected

between 1987 and 1992, has been completed.  All sources have given closely similar results,

indicating that each contained the same major strain of agent.  In addition, strain typing of

two Swiss BSE sources has shown them to be closely related to UK BSE.<p>



In parallel, four transmissions of natural sheep scrapie have been completed, one from a

flock in which a food-borne source in infection was suspected.  None of these resembled BSE

in their transmission characteristics to mice, suggesting that different strains of agent were

present in the sheep and cattle sources.  As in previous studies, the results from the range

of sheep scrapie sources were very variable, in contrast with the uniformity seen with the

BSE cattle sources.  A further scrapie transmission is in progress from a sheep from a flock

with a suspected food-borne source of infection.<p>



Serial passages in different mouse genotypes have been completed, up to the third mouse-to-mouse

passage, from three of the BSE sources and one scrapie source.  The same two

mouse-passaged strains of agent  have been isolated from each BSE source and these differ

from the two strains isolated from the scrapie source.  Further mouse-to-mouse passage lines

have been set up from other sheep scrapie sources, in an attempt to identify any overlap in

the mouse-passaged strains isolated from BSE and scrapie.<p>



Transmissions have been set up from genetically defined Cheviot sheep with natural scrapie

from the NPU flock, in order to characterise the strains of scrapie involved.  The selection,

characterisation and biological cloning of scrapie strains from established isolates has

continued on a small scale.  Stocks of mouse-passaged strains for use in other projects are

also routinely generated in this project.  <p>



<A NAME="4"><h2>Post-transcriptional control of PrP mRNA expression</h2></A>



Reporter gene constructs have been made containing various sections and deletions of the PrP

3'-UTR downstream of the CAT gene.  In <i>in vitro</i> cell-free systems, expression of CAT

protein has not been markedly affected by any of the PrP 3'UTR regions.  However,

constructs which will allow similar studies to take place in cultured cells (N2a), have given

more promising results and an additional set of deletion mutants is now being investigated.<p>



<A NAME="5"><h2>5' and 3' non-coding regions of PrP mRNA</h2></A>



Susceptibility to scrapie has been shown to be associated with polymorphisms in the ovine

PrP protein coding region.  Novel disease-associated amino acid changes have also been

shown in goats.  However, some sheep and goats encoding the same PrP protein variant still

exhibit different susceptibility to scrapie, which might be explained by variation of PrP

expression linked to polymorphisms outside the coding region.  Several new polymorphisms

in the 3'-non-coding region have now been found, some of them between alleles encoding

the same PrP protein sequence.  These sequence variations are currently used to analyse the

expression of different ovine PrP alleles.<p>



<A NAME="6"><h2>PrP structure</h2></A>



The conversion of the normal form of the prion protein (PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>c</FONT></SUP>) to its protease-resistant

isoform (PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP>) is a key process in the development of scrapie and related prion disease.

PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP> is enriched in preparations of infectious particles and, either by itself or in association

with other molecules, is regarded by many as the infectious agent.  The structure of PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP>

(and infectivity) is resistant to heat and chemicals which destroy most other micro-organisms

and this stability has been considered as a critical factor in the transmission of scrapie from

sheep to cattle in the early 1980s which initiated the epidemic of BSE.<p>



Recently, in collaboration with Dr B Caughey and colleagues at the NIH Rocky Mountain

Laboratory, Montana, the conversion of bovine PrP (PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>c</FONT></SUP>) to a protease-resistant isoform has

been achieved <i>in vitro</i> using bovine PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP> as a catalyst.  The parts of the protein molecule

needed for this conversion and for the replication and inter-species transmission of disease

are under investigation at the IAH and elsewhere, using recombinant DNA methods to

produce native and mutant prion proteins in cells and transgenic mice.  While this work aims

to delineate regions of the PrP molecule important for these processes, it will be difficult to

interpret in terms of mechanism because the secondary and tertiary structure of the PrP

protein and the effect of various mutations and deletions on this structure are unknown.<p>



Parallel work on the natural forms of PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>c</FONT></SUP> and PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP> has been hindered by the lack of protein

and its aggregated, highly-insoluble nature, but some recent studies have provided clues to

their structures.  In other laboratories, spectral changes monitored by circular dichroism or

fluorescence during the thermal or chemical (irreversible) denaturation of PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>27-30</FONT></SUP> (an active

fragment of PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP>) indicate a more complex 'melt' of this fibrillar form of the protein, 

possibly involving a transition state with similar properties to a 'molten globule.'  Circular dichroism (CD),

Fourier-transform infra-red spectroscopy (FT-IR) and fluorescence

measurements on PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>c</FONT></SUP> and PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP> give estimates of a high alpha-helix secondary structure in

PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>c</FONT></SUP>, less in PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP> and least in

PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>27-30</FONT></SUP>.  These spectroscopic data and computer simulations

of the secondary and tertiary structure of PrP have led Dr F Cohen and his colleagues in San

Francisco to propose a four-helix bundle model of PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>c</FONT></SUP> and a mechanism involving the

switch of one or more of these helices to beta-sheet structure when this normal isoform

changes to its protease-resistant forms (PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP> and

PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>27-30</FONT></SUP>).<p>



The thermodynamic stabilities and folding mechanisms of proteins have been extensively

studied in recent years by using genetic engineering techniques to manipulate the co-valent

structures of polypeptide chains.  By comparing proteins that differ by only one or a few

amino-acid residues produced by mutation of genes <i>in vitro</i>, the roles of individual residues

and interactions in folding and stability can be tested.  To complement studies on the natural

forms of PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>c</FONT></SUP> and PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP> and

on the Institute's transgenic programme of research on the

biological aspects of PrP in the spongiform encephalopathies, a programme has been initiated

to investigate the structure, stability and folding of the wild-type and mutant,  recPrP

proteins.  Milligram quantities of recPrP are being produced and purified.   During the year,

a new group has been formed and appropriate analytical equipment installed (circular

dichroism spectropolarimeter, fluorimeter, electro-spray mass spectrometer, laser light

scattering instrument, plasmon resonance spectroscopy and a crystallisation oven) to exploit

this material fully.<p>



<A NAME="7"><h2>Cytotoxicity of PrP</h2></A>



The abnormal form of the prion protein (PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP>), a synthetic prion protein peptide fragment

(PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>106-126</FONT></SUP>) and fragments of the Alzheimer's protein precursor (APP) have been shown to be

cytotoxic <i>in vitro</i>.  Synchronous, clonal cell models, originally developed to study the

toxicity of the Alzheimer's disease amyloid peptide, A25-35, have been used to investigate

the actions of PrP peptides.  The cytotoxicity of the PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>106-126</FONT></SUP> was found to depend on its

state of aggregation and the cellular expression of PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>c</FONT></SUP>, and was independent of a loss of

MTT reduction activity in the absence of cell death associated with the cellular effects of

A25-35.  These factors may play a role in the lesion-specificity of different pathological

phenotypes of prion-protein.<p>



<A NAME="8"><h2>Recombinant PrP</h2></A>



Recombinant murine PrP protein expressed from mammalian cells is being used for

structure/function studies.  In addition to truncated aglycosyl Prp protein, material is also

being purified from a cell line that stably secretes truncated glycosylated PrP.  Studies on

improved stability and purification are progressing well. <p>



<A NAME="9"><h2>Crystalline PrP</h2></A>



Good quality crystals of recPrP protein are the key to the high resolution X-ray diffraction

analysis of the tertiary structure of the protein.  Empirical screening of crystallisation

conditions continue.<p>



The protein is soluble in the presence of significant quantities of non-polar water-miscible

solvents in keeping with its hydrophobic properties deduced from previous detergent solubilisation studies.<p>



Further progress will be assisted by recent improvements in purification procedures.<p>



<A NAME="10"><h2>Replication of PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP></h2></A>



The work has focused on a variety of extensive studies principally aimed at the unequivocal

demonstration that rat PC12 cells can efficiently take up and replicate mouse-passaged scrapie

agent.  The growth and nerve growth factor-mediated neuronal differentiation of scrapie-proficient

cells obtained from Dr R Rubenstein (USA) were optimised. This included the six-week maintenance

of attached neuronal cells for the reported duration of maximal

accumulation of the scrapie-specific isoform of PrP protein (PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP>).  Various methods used

for the preparation and application of the scrapie-infected mouse brain homogenate were tried

but no <i>de novo</i> rat PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP> could be detected despite the unequivocal detection of mouse PrPSc

in the inoculum.  Polyclonal antisera raised in mice to recombinant rat PrP protein purified

from an <i>E coli</i> expression system was produced but has yet to be evaluated.<p>



<A NAME="11"><h2>A basis for prophylaxis</h2></A>



Plasmon resonance studies have been used to investigate the hypothesis that a range

of anti-scrapie prophylactic compounds act by interacting with a specific region on the PrP protein.<p>



A synthetic peptide to this region has been shown to bind to one of these compounds under

physiological buffer conditions.  Another peptide of identical amino acid composition but of

differing primary sequence does not bind.  Chemically similar but non-prophylactic

compounds also failed to bind to the PrP peptide.<p>



<A NAME="12"><h2>Markers for susceptibility in sheep</h2></A>



PrP genotypes of sheep affected with natural scrapie and those of healthy flock mates are

being compared.  Differences have been noted between outbreaks and between flocks.  This

may be due to differences in the strain of natural scrapie affecting the flock or may reflect

breed differences in the sheep themselves.<p>



The most important variants of the PrP gene are those differing at codon 136 and 171. 

Valine at codon 136(V<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>136</FONT></SUB>) has a dominant association with incidence of scrapie but is not

found in all breeds of sheep.  Glutamine at codon 171 (Q<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>171</FONT></SUB>) has a recessive association with

scrapie and has been found in all breeds of sheep examined so far.  <p>



The NPU Cheviot flock had 45 deaths from natural scrapie between 1986 and 1995.  Of

these cases 39 were analysed for disease-linked PrP gene polymorphisms and all encode V<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>136</FONT></SUB>

on at least one allele with 79% homozygous (VV<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>136</FONT></SUB>) and 21% valine/alanine heterozygotes

(VA<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>136</FONT></SUB>).  Mean survival time was 888 and 1482 days for VV<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>136</FONT></SUB> and VA<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>136</FONT></SUB> animals

respectively.  VV<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>136</FONT></SUB> animals were all at great risk of disease if allowed to live long enough. 

However, scrapie occurred only in a specific subgroup of VA<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>136</FONT></SUB> sheep, survival advantage

depending on VA<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>136</FONT></SUB> animals being heterozygous for other polymorphisms at codon 154 or

171.<p>



The flock history has been recorded in great detail since its foundation in 1960.

However there was no strong evidence for simple maternal or paternal transmission of disease other

than inheritance of PrP genotype.<p>



In a Suffolk flock with scrapie, cases occurred in animals according to their PrP genotype

at codon 171.  QQ<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>171</FONT></SUB> sheep were at great risk of scrapie whereas those which were

arginine/glutamine heterozygotes (RQ) were at less risk and RR<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>171</FONT></SUB> animals appeared to be

resistant.  A histidine codon (H<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>171</FONT></SUB>) can also be found at this position in Suffolk sheep but this

did not occur in scrapie-affected animals.<p>



<A NAME="13"><h2>An ante-mortem test </h2></A>



Antibody reagents to ruminant PrP have been produced in chicken eggs using recombinant

PrP as the immunogen.  Such anti-PrP antibodies require extensive purification before use. 

Ion exchange-purified antibody treated with pepsin to create Fab' fragments have high

specificity and sensitivity to PrP in ruminant brain and spleen homogenates.  Affinity-purified

antibody shows similar or enhanced properties.  Monoclonal antibodies which recognise

species-specific epitopes have also been produced.<p>



Extraction of ruminant tissue with the detergent Sarkosyl plus differential digestion with

proteinase K followed by immunoblotting provides an assay for PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP>.  The purified chicken

antibody reagents are sufficiently sensitive and specific to detect PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP> in ruminant brain and

spleen.  However, PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP> cannot be unequivocally detected in lymph node extracts with the

current technology.  PrP<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>Sc</FONT></SUP> has been detected in brains and spleens from all natural scrapie

cases examined so far but not in controls.<p>



<A NAME="14"><h2>Natural modes of transmission</h2></A>



The incidence of natural scrapie in the NPU's flock of Cheviots is linked to PrP genotype.

The flock is maintained as two breeding lines, one (susceptible: 'positive') which has

endemic natural scrapie and the other (resistant: 'negative') which is entirely free from

clinical manifestation of the disease.<p>



The positive line is being bred to carry specific PrP genes which are linked to susceptibility

to experimental inoculation but resistant to the natural disease (VA<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>136</FONT></SUB>/RQ<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>171</FONT></SUB>), thereby

controlling its incidence by manipulating genetic frequency.  The negative line is being bred

for different PrP genes (AA<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>136</FONT></SUB>/RR<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>171</FONT></SUB>, RQ<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>171</FONT></SUB>, QQ<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>171</FONT></SUB>) which also never allow natural scrapie

to develop and in which transmission experiments can be achieved without compromise.  A

further line, completely segregated from the first two, is being bred to generate an high

incidence of natural scrapie, by increasing the frequency of susceptible PrP genes (VV<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>136</FONT></SUB>,

VA<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>136</FONT></SUB>/QQ<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>171</FONT></SUB>) so that studies on the pathogenesis of natural scrapie can continue.<p>



Recovery of CNS, lymphoreticular and placental tissues from sheep of different PrP

genotypes for immunolabelling by histology and western blotting of the PrP protein is

continuing.<p>



Work continues on the transmission to mice from sheep tissues of inoculated and

uninoculated animals to establish whether a carrier state of infection exists and to characterise

natural isolates of scrapie from the Skedsbush flock.<p>



<A NAME="15"><h2>Transmission of BSE to sheep and goats</h2></A>



This study is nearing completion with three sheep surviving from oral challenge with BSE,

and three goats and two sheep surviving oral challenge with an isolate of natural scrapie.<p>



The results have shown that sheep (from both negative and positive lines--<i>see</i> previous

report) and goats are susceptible to infection by intracerebral inoculation and by oral dosing

with homogenates of cow brain known to be carrying the BSE agent. <p>



Comparative transmission results between BSE and a natural isolate of scrapie do not support

significant differences in incubation data.  It is apparent from transmission studies in mice

that when BSE is passaged in sheep, the strain characteristics do not differ much from those

of primary BSE.<p>



<A NAME="16"><h2>Rendering methods</h2></A>



It has been suggested that meat-and-bone meal became the dietary vehicle for BSE in cattle

because of the large-scale abandonment of organic solvent extraction of greaves in the late

1970s.  It is postulated that the application of hot solvent to the already heat-treated greaves,

and the subsequent evaporation process utilising dry heat and steam, had traditionally

suppressed the titre of infectivity in meat-and-bone meal to a sufficient extent that it was not

an effective oral dose for cattle.  There were two objections to the hypothesis:<p>



<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>The scrapie agent is known to be little affected by organic solvents generally
although the efficacy of those specifically used by the rendering industry, <i>ie</i>
hexane, benzene, petroleum and perchlorethylene, had not been tested
previously.<p>

<LI>The temperature of 100<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>o</FONT></SUP>C used to evaporate the solvents is unlikely to have
much effect.<p>
</UL>

Nevertheless there was sufficient concern to encourage a project designed to determine

whether exposure to the relevant hot solvents and/or heat during the evaporation process has

any significant inactivating effect.<p>



The starting material was pooled mouse spleen infected with either the 301V strain of BSE

agent or the 22A strain of scrapie agent.  The experiments are still in progress but in the

study using hexane with 301V there appears to be little inactivation by the solvent extraction

or the evaporation processes, either individually or in combination.<p>



<A NAME="17"><h2>Rendering under commercial conditions</h2></A>



Facsimiles of the rendering processes used within the EU were conducted in commercial

pilot-scale rendering equipment using raw materials spiked with either BSE or scrapie agent.

BSE infectivity survived in meat and bone meal produced by four of these procedures, and

these have now been modified or outlawed by the EU.  The scrapie-spiked study is still in

progress but it can already be seen that meat and bone meal produced by all processes,

except those involving steam under pressure, have produced infected meat and bone meal. 

<p>



<A NAME="18"><h2>Chemical and physical inactivation</h2></A>



It is well known that scrapie agent is relatively resistant to inactivation by conventional

microbiological decontamination procedures.  The purpose of this project is to determine 

whether the same is true for BSE agent, and to re-assess the status of some existing

procedures with regard to scrapie agent because of doubts about existing data.  To date, the

following have been established:<p>



<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>BSE agent survives exposure to formol saline.<p>

<LI>BSE agent is inactivated within 30 minutes by concentrations of sodium
hypochlorite that are known to be effective with scrapie agent.  Thus the
recommendation that applies to the inactivation of scrapie agent, <i>ie</i> exposure
to a solution containing 20,000ppm available chlorine for 1 hour, is applicable
to BSE agent.<p>

<LI>Solutions of sodium dichloroisocyanurate, containing the same levels of
available chlorine that were present in the effective sodium hypochlorite
solutions, are not effective with BSE agent.<p>

<LI>Exposure to 2M sodium hydroxide for 2 hours does not inactivate scrapie
agent but is effective against BSE agent, although it survived a 1 hour
exposure.  These data contradict those in the study which was the basis of the
American recommendation that a 1 hour exposure to 1M sodium hydroxide
can be regarded as completely effective.  However, the bioassays in this
present study were more sensitive than those in the American study.<p>

<LI>BSE and scrapie agents have survived porous-load autoclaving at 134-138<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>o</FONT></SUP>C
for &#62;=18 minutes when exposed as 341-mg (average) macerates of infected
brain.  These data challenge the current UK standard for porous-load
autoclave decontamination of scrapie-like agents which is a cycle of 18
minutes at 134-138<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>o</FONT></SUP>C.  The scrapie inactivation data upon which the current
recommendation is based were derived from experiments where 50-mg
macerates of infected brain were used.  The present data probably result from
the use of larger tissue samples but animal and human health authorities have
been unable to advise as to what the maximum weight of tissue is that might
be encountered in practice.<p>

<LI>BSE agent has been inactivated by a 30-minute exposure to gravity-displacement
autoclaving at 132<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>o</FONT></SUP>C but the effect of a 1 hour exposure (a
procedure recommended currently in America for inactivation of scrapie-like
agents) is not yet known.  This experiment is still in progress.<p>

<LI>After mouse brain fixed in PLP has been exposed to concentrated formic acid
for an hour, an estimated 10<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>3.2</FONT></SUP> ID<SUB><FONT SIZE=-2>50</FONT></SUB>/g survive.

This is two logs greater than
that recorded for formol-fixed scrapie-infected brain.  Further experiments are
in progress to determine whether this is a property of 301V or is an effect of
the fixative.  The effect of formic acid treatment on PLP-fixed tissue is also
being assessed using BSE-infected cow brain and mouse brain infected with
either the 87V or ME7 strains of scrapie agent.<p>

<LI>Microwave irradiation does not inactivate scrapie agent.  However, an
interesting observation was that the difference in incubation periods between
IM and VM mice injected with irradiated inoculum was exaggerated compared
with recipients of infectious boiled inoculum.<p>

<LI>Mouse brain infected with the 22A strain of scrapie agent which was
immersed in ethanol for 48 hours remained infectious after porous-load
autoclaving at 136<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>o</FONT></SUP>C for 18 minutes.  The same brain material immersed
in saline for 48 hours was inactivated by the autoclaving process.<p>
</UL>



<A NAME="19"><h2>Review of autoclave protocols</h2></A>



In 1984 the DoH recommended a porous-load autoclaving cycle of 134-138<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>o</FONT></SUP>C for 18 minutes

for decontamination of CJD agent.  This was based upon studies using 50-mg macerates of

mouse brain infected with two mouse-passaged strains of scrapie agent (22A and 139A); both

strains had been inactivated by exposure to 136<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>o</FONT></SUP>C for 4 minutes.<p>



In early experiments carried out at the IAH, BSE and scrapie agents were found to survive

partially when infected 341-mg brain macerates were exposed to 134-138<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>o</FONT></SUP>C for &#62;=18

minutes.  This present study is designed to determine the effect of 50-mg compared with

375-mg sample weights when subjected to cycles at 134<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>o</FONT></SUP>C, 136<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>o</FONT></SUP>C and 138<SUP><FONT SIZE=-2>o</FONT></SUP>C for 9, 18, 30 or 60

minutes using the 301V strain of BSE agent, and the 22A and 263K strains of scrapie agent. 

A further aim was to expose the three agents at comparable titre to an autoclaving regime

that is known to permit partial survival of 22A, in order to determine the ranking of

thermostability for the three agents used.<p>



The experiment is still in progress and it is too early to draw any conclusions.  However,

it is evident that 263K and 301V are surviving autoclaving cycles that fall within the scope

of the UK recommendations.  As anticipated, the larger tissue samples appear to be more

difficult to inactivate than the smaller ones.<p>



